{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"40bac6ba-0ee9-49d7-a8bf-aeeecb3ca24c","content":"The `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` platform-specific should still work in .NET 10 MAUI. If it's not applying, the most common cause after upgrade is a missing or stale namespace import. Here's the correct XAML:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n    xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"\n    x:Class=\"MyApp.MainPage\">\n\n    <!-- your content here -->\n\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nIf that still doesn't take effect after a clean rebuild (`dotnet clean && dotnet build`), apply it from code-behind instead:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration;\nusing Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;\n\npublic partial class MainPage : ContentPage\n{\n    public MainPage()\n    {\n        InitializeComponent();\n        On<iOS>().SetUseSafeArea(true);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Common gotcha after TFM upgrade:** if you're using `Shell`, make sure the property is on each `ContentPage`, not on the `Shell` itself — `UseSafeArea` is a `Page`-level property. Also do a full clean/rebuild after changing from `net9.0-ios` to `net10.0-ios`, as stale platform caches can cause this exact symptom.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b7154433-8250-4a89-a9ea-038ed09239c4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a knowledge question about a framework change.\n\nIn .NET 10 (which would be a preview/upcoming release as of April 2026), there were changes to how safe area insets are handled in MAUI for iOS.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` was the platform-specific way to handle safe areas on iOS. In .NET 10, Microsoft changed the safe area handling. The key change was that `UseSafeArea` was deprecated/changed in favor of using padding-based approaches or the new safe area APIs.\n\n\nActually, I should be more careful about what I'm confident in here. The `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` property has been part of .NET MAUI for a while, and I'm not entirely certain about the specifics of what changed in .NET 10 without being able to verify the exact breaking changes.\n\nGiven that the user upgraded to .NET 10 and `UseSafeArea=\"True\"` stopped working, the most likely explanations are that the API was deprecated, there's a bug, or the behavior changed significantly. The standard alternatives for handling safe areas in .NET MAUI include using `Padding` with platform-specific adjustments or leveraging newer safe area handling mechanisms, though I should acknowledge the limits of what I can confidently recommend without more current documentation. I could also handle this in the code-behind using the platform-specific API, or manually adjust padding based on safe area insets. But I'm realizing the API might have shifted in .NET 10—either `UseSafeArea` changed behavior, or there's a new cross-platform approach I should consider instead. Setting the safe area property via XAML or programmatically through the iOS platform configuration should handle this, though I'm second-guessing whether .NET 10 changed something about how this works under the hood. I'm uncertain about the exact .NET 10 API changes, so I'll provide the standard `UseSafeArea` approach along with code-behind and manual padding alternatives, then note that they should check the migration docs if there's a specific breaking change in their version. worked fine.\" So the property itself was working. Now in .NET 10 it's not working, which suggests either an API change or a regression. I'll provide the standard XAML approach and some alternatives to help them troubleshoot.","outputToke